With an increase in the temperature, the intensity of the CD fluorescence changes nonmonotonically. To illustrate this fact Fig. 5
                         shows the carbon dot fluorescence spectra at temperatures of 301, 358, and 442 K. One can see that an increase in temperature first leads to fluorescence quenching, and then, with further increasing the temperature, the fluorescence intensity enhances and returns almost to its initial value. An increase in the temperature is also accompanied by a slight increase in the full widths at half maxima of the fluorescence bands and by shifts of their maxima to the short-wavelength side. The latter effect is most obvious in the case of the short wavelength band (band 1) of the spectrum (Fig. 6
                        ). In passing, it can be noted that NR in solution also demonstrates a blue shift of the emission peak in individual solvents as temperature increases [35]. Due to the thermally induced broadening of the overlapping spectral bands 1 and 2, they practically merge into one asymmetric band with an extended long-wavelength wing at high temperatures.
